<h1 style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;</h1><h1 style="text-align: left;">Oldrich Halas</h1>
<h2>1967-2024</h2>
<img alt="Oldrich Halas" class="center" height="499" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/db/Oldrich_Halas_compositor.jpg" width="313" />

<h2 stlye="text-align: left;"> About the Composer: </h2>

<h3 style="text-align: left;">Place of Birth: </h3>
<p>Potosi, Bolivia</p>

<h3 style="text-align: left;">Biography</h3>

<p>Composer, teacher, and graphic artist, Halas was born in La Paz, Bolivia in 1967 to a Potosi mother and a Czech father. His mother is from Potosi, Bolivia and his father is  mother and a Czech father. In 1986 he made his debut as a composer at a concert in La Paz shared with Alberto Villalpando and and Willy Pozadas. That same year, Halas entered the National Conservatory of Music in La Paz. However, shortly after, he traveled to the Federal Republic of Germany, where he continued his studies at the Pfälzische Musikakademie (Palatinate Music Academy) in the city of Speyer in the Rhineland Palatinate and then at the Higher School of Music from the city of Karlsruhe. In 1996 he returned to Bolivia.</p>
<p>Halas works include compositions for piano, vocal, solo instruments, chamber music, choral music, concert music, symphonic and incidental. His compositional work can be recognized according to the place and time in which it was generated. Halas juvenile work (1980 – 1986) includes a large collection of works, the vast majority outside the official catalog of works and the vast majority unpublished. Works from this time of production include: the cantata El Canto de los Sepulcros (The Song for the Tombs) (1984) for soloists, mixed choir and chamber ensemble composed for the Bolivian Choral Society; the Allegro Brusco Op.3 (1985); the Misa Interdicta (the Prohibited Mass) Op.6 (1987) and the melodrama for baritone and piano on the homonymous narrative by F. Kafka Report for an Academy Op.4 (1986). His European period (1987 – 1994) begins with the composition Concertino for transverse flute and string orchestra Op.8 (1988);  Réquiem para la Selva Amazónica (Requiem for the Amazon Jungle) Op.10 (1990); wind quintet Op.12 (1992); and Toccata for solo cello Op.14 (1993). Halas Bolivian period (1995 to the present) include works that seek inspiration from Bolivian traditions and popular music. Representative works include Cantos Líticos (Lithic Songs) Op.16 for voice and piano;  Álbum para un Ratón Criollo (Album for a Creole Mouse) Op.20 (1998), El Cóndor y la Tormenta (the Condor and the Storm) Op.24 (2001), Alasita - I Book Op. 28 (2004), Jacha Flowers Homenaje Blues (Jacha Flowers Homenaje Blues) Op.29 (2004), El Entierro del Pepino  (The Cucumber Burial) Op.32 (2010), Waca Concertino Op.26 (2006 - 2018) and the burlesque for solo saxophone Chuta Cholero Op.41 (2020).In addition to his solo work, Halas  has also worked to create original sound tracks for films. He has worked for Oscar García on the soundtracks for movies by Jorge Sanjinés and Marcos Loayza. In 2005, he made the original music for the Fernando Vargas film “Di buen día a Papá” (Say good day to Dad). </p> 
<p> As a music teacher, he has thrived as an academic authority in various positions. Between 2002 and 2003 he was a professor of music at the Bolivian Catholic University. He was a member of the Board of Directors of the National Conservatory of Music (2002-2007), head of the Academic Unit of the National Conservatory of Music (2008-2010), executive director of the National Conservatory of Music in La Paz. (2010-2013) and rector of the new Plurinational Conservatory of Music (2013-2015).</p>
<p> Halas has been distinguished with several prizes and recognitions as an artist and composer. In  2009 he received a recognition for his 20 years of career in the dissemination of music, artistic and cultural events, granted by the Honorable Congress of the Republic of Bolivia. He also received recognition from the Parliamentary Brigade of the City of La Paz, and the Medal of Cultural Merit, for Musical composition by the Bolivian Association "Pro Arte" in 2014.</p>
